therapists.additional_information: I am a queer, CIS-gendered, non-gender conforming, immigrant.  I identify as Chinese and Taiwanese.

I am an Asian American mindfulness practitioner who specializes in issues of acculturation, racial identity, intersectionality, stress, anxiety, perfectionism, communication, and loving self-kindness. I'm passionate about helping folks build a sense of belonging and healthy entitlement.
I believe therapy can be a radical, healing experience, and I attend my own therapy sessions on a regular basis.
I work individually with young adults, adults and elderly.

I am a LCSW based in Berkeley, CA. I offer weekly, long-term, depth therapy for adults, and couples and EMDR therapy. I work from a psychodynamic, attachment and relational lens and hold strong importance around sociocultural issues. I work mainly with adults and couples who have experienced any of the following: anxiety, adult attachment issues, relationship issues/interpersonal effectiveness, identity work (cultural, social), adult children of immigrants, life transitions (new moms, career change, etc), ppl who work in tech, low-self esteem, adults who had narcissistic parents or partners, grief & loss, PTSD and complex trauma.

I'm a Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist practicing in the San Francisco Bay Area. I work with teens, adults and couples. I specialize in anxiety, depression, stress management, family and relationship issues. I work predominantly with Asian and Asian American clients, many who want to feel seen and understood by a culturally competent therapist.

As a non-pathologizing humanistic-existential Gestalt therapist, I will meet you exactly where you are. I recognize that you are the expert of your own experience and that you already possess the ability and skills that will aid you in healing your pain and suffering. As your empathic witness, advocate, and guide, I will help you increase your self-awareness, self-acceptance, and sense of agency through mindful observation, personal exploration, and collaborative experimentation. Essentially, I will help you re-examine your life and re-experience yourself and others, in different as well as new meaningful and healing ways.

Hieu is a Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW) in CA and practices in the City of Brea. With more than 10 years of combined experience serving immigrant and refugee communities across three counties in California (San Diego, Los Angeles, Orange Counties) as well as serving other marginalized communities such as those living with vision impairments and hearing loss or those living with severe persistent & mental illness, those who identify with the LGBTQ+ community, those living with HIV/AIDS, Hieu now specializes in supporting those who experience mood disorders, anxiety, or depression from unresolved trauma as a Certified EMDR Therapist.

I am a licensed marriage and family therapist specializing in individual therapy for adults struggling with depression, anxiety, trauma, self-esteem, grief/loss, and other life transitions. I am trained and certified in cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) and a certified grief counseling specialist (CGCS). I have experience working with a diverse population including young adults, adults, LGBTQ, homeless/low-income, children of immigrants, cross-cultural families, and bereaved clients. I tailor my sessions according to the individual needs of each client and I believe that therapy should be warm, collaborative, and rewarding.

Dr. Sun-Suslow is a licensed clinical neuropsychologist in the state of California. She specializes in working with adults and older adults living with neurological and psychiatric disorders. She helps diagnose brain disorders, assess cognitive and behavioral functioning, and design effective treatments. She received her doctoral degree from University of Miami and completed an predoctoral internship at the UC San Diego/VA San Diego Healthcare System joint training program. She also completed a 2-year postdoctoral fellowship at UC San Diego in clinical neuropsychology. She is dedicated and excited to serve the AAPI community.

Experience include: author of 3 books on children’s behavior- Corwin Press and twenty e-books on therapy and couple therapy; dvds on child development and behavior; community mental health, SED and vocational and welfare-to-work programs, Head Start, supervising a high school mental health clinic, supervising therapists, private practice since 1994 licensure.  16 years in ECE, elementary & secondary teaching credentials, college instructor psychology master program- Western Institute for Social Research, and service on the Board of Directors of the California Kindergarten Association, California Association of Marriage & Family Therapists.

I am committed to your health and well being. I am here to listen because your story matters. I am here to help you find perspective, to slow down, to reconnect, to breathe. I am here to assist you to identify and articulate your needs and to provide you with options to meet those needs. It’s important for me to provide a safe environment so we can build trust with one another. A trusting relationship is the foundation for discovering and processing  your truth, and ultimately healing. Let’s meet and see if we can move forward together.

I am a Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist and a Registered Drama Therapist. I have experience of working with a wide range of clients, between the ages of 5 and 101 years old, facing various challenges in life. I feel particularly passionate about supporting and empowering people struggling with effects of childhood abuse/trauma. I might incorporate various therapeutic approaches, including expressive arts-based/experiential interventions, according to your unique individual needs. Please reach out, and we can briefly talk over the phone to see if I could be the right therapist for you.​

I am a licensed clinical psychologist that practices using a psychodynamic theoretical background. This means that we will explore how childhood experiences and current relationships impact the way you think, feel, and behave. I’ll help you see patterns and make connections between your past and present, so that you will be better informed to make wise decisions about your future. I’m not here to tell you what to do – instead I want to walk alongside you through your ups and downs. In therapy, I will create an open, safe, exploratory space for you to feel known and cared for.
https://drive.google.com/file/d/1hhFzuQ8nk5waLT2_M1N-RpjLgRNqqHu_/view?usp=drivesdk

I am a clinical psychologist licensed in California. A few of my specialties include young adults identity development, trauma, depression, anxiety, spiritual integration in therapy. Many of my clients seek out my help to process issues such as life transitions, repeated unhelpful patterns in life, or internal conflicts such as perpetuate feelings of guilt. My treatment approach is to foster safety through providing a warm, non-judgmental environment. Through honest feedback, you will be equipped to dive deeper into your inner world to find further understanding and grace for yourself. Please visit my website for more information about me.

Dr. So is a clinical psychologist licensed in the state of California. Her specialties include adult ADHD, adjustment issues, college students, identity/diversity issues, family issues, interpersonal issues, depression, anxiety, OCD, and chronic pain. 

Dr. So offers an integrative approach to therapy, tailoring interventions to meet the individual needs of clients.
I am an Associate Marriage and Family Therapist in California.

I wish people knew therapy can be helpful even for those who are not used to talking about their struggles. I have had the pleasure of being a therapist for almost 10 years.  I’ve helped individuals acknowledge and identify the root of their pain, problem solve difficulties, move forward with strategies that allow them to tackle stress, and build meaningful relationships. In addition to owning my own private practice, I have a podcast called Books Between Sessions and am a writer, which helps me work toward decreasing stigma toward mental health and mental illness.

Dr. Velarde is a licensed clinical psychologist and Director of Training of Fuller Theological Seminary’s on-campus mental health clinic. She specializes in areas of grief/loss, cultural issues, relational issues, and spirituality/religion. Dr. Velarde’s approach to treatment is collaborative and relational, utilizing Psychodynamic, Humanistic, and CBT approaches.

[Not Accepting New Clients] I am a licensed clinical social worker, therapist, and a group practice owner based in Sherman Oaks, CA. I commonly help people who are experiencing anxiety, depression and/ or trauma. I work with my clients to help them unpack how their earlier years in childhood and adolescence can impact how they experience themselves and their relationships. I work with clients to help them make connections from the past to the present while also teaching coping skills to help improve their symptoms and interpersonal relationships.

I am a licensed clinical social worker with over 12 years of experience direct clinical work with adults who have mental health issues. My focus is to create a supportive and accepting environment for everyone anywhere, especially minorities and socially disadvantaged. My vast experience taught me that the most important aspect of clinical work is caring for the person and understanding the challenges that keeps them away from their happiness.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Optum, Beacon, Cigna, Medicare, Molina, Tricare West

therapists.additional_information:
Dr. Betsy Chung is a licensed psychologist in California, and has been practicing therapy for over 10 years. Before starting her private practice, Dr. Chung had experience working in both in-patient and out-patient treatment settings, treated conditions like anxiety and mood disorders, substance abuse, and has received special training in trauma and parenting skills.

Over the course of her career, Dr. Chung realized her passion for helping clients achieve life satisfaction by teaching them how to approach life in a more purposeful way, resulting in a healthier relationship with the self and others.

I specialize in treatment of anxiety and trauma. I believe that everyone inherently has the ability to heal and grow. I will walk alongside you and guide you in your journey of healing and self-discovery. As a Chinese American immigrant, I understand the importance of our cultural values and past experiences in how they shape our identity and choices we make. I speak Mandarin Chinese and prioritize clients that are looking for a Mandarin speaking therapist.  I will support and empower you to gain the confidence to lead a more fulfilling life! Feel free to email me to schedule a free 15 minute phone consultation to see if we are a good fit.

I’m Taiwanese-American and a proud Angeleno. I am a career changer and formerly worked in advertising and marketing for years prior to becoming a therapist. My path to becoming a psychotherapist is shaped by my interest in human behavior, passion for social justice, and personal life experiences. I obtained my MSW from USC and worked with adults from diverse cultural and socio-economic backgrounds. Deepening our understanding of the human experience is something I hold with the deepest respect and care. I provide a safe, non-judgmental space to support you through life transitions and exploration of family of origin dynamics and identity.

Hatty (she/her) is a marriage and family therapist and Brainspotting practitioner who has been practicing for over 11 years. As the founder of a thriving group practice in Los Angeles, California, she has met with over a thousand people from diverse backgrounds in psychotherapy, counseling groups, and wellness workshops. She supports people to deepen connection with themselves and the most important people in their lives. She also writes about mental health on her Instagram account @hattyjlee and her work has been featured in multiple editorials, including Women's Health Magazine and Reader's Digest.

Our wellness is paramount to our livelihood – physical, emotional, social, spiritual, career, and financial. Jane is passionate about holding space for building a therapeutic relationship that fosters a positive and authentic connection with others and with themselves for personal growth, gain insight, and empowerment for real, well-balanced life.

Jane Kwon received a B.A. in Psychology from the University of California, Irvine. Jane earned an M.A. in Clinical Psychology with an emphasis in Marriage and Family Therapy from Pepperdine University’s Graduate School of Education and Psychology.

Therapy is an intentional and meaningful process through life's challenges.  As an anxiety and trauma specialist, I provide ongoing support to recreate calm, restoration of self and redefining a meaningful life that is worth living.  I work with high-achieving adults experiencing high stress, anxiety and depression which may often result in low self-esteem and reduced self-worthiness. I am passionate about working with individuals around the issues of Asian-American cultural conflict and intergenerational family trauma. My goal is to support you develop a healthier relationship with your authentic self. Providing therapy for all CA residents.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Out of Network (Superbills for PPO/POS plans)

therapists.additional_information: As a first generation openly gay, Christian, and Korean American psychotherapist, I specialize in working with people who identify with traditionally marginalized and oppressed groups such as LGBTQ, racial and cultural minorities. I also have unique insight into the Asian American experience.

There’s such a profound power in the therapy process of finding and owning your story. I’m always amazed to witness how resilient my clients are. Often times my clients already had what it took – they just needed some guidance, support, and tools along the way. And it’s truly a privilege for me to share that journey.
My passion is helping individuals, couples, and families to connect to themselves, to each other, and to bigger meaning & purpose by becoming the most authentic and truest version of themselves. With the right help, you can start to accept and love being yourself and your loved ones (even it's for the first time).

I enjoy working with fellow queer artists and creative professionals, as well as teens, and couples. I have a BFA in Art and Environmental Studies from the University of Washington in Seattle. I also have an MFA in Photography from Otis College of Art and Design. And an MA in Clinical Psychology from Antioch University in Los Angeles. In addition to my private practice, I serve as Faculty in the Masters in Counseling Department at Cal State University San Bernardino. I am also a part of a research team based in LA, developing ideas to best serve our clients and this work has been published in the Journal of Contemporary Narrative Therapy.

Min is a LMFT who obtained her Master's degree from University of Southern California and has extensive experience working with children (0-14 y/o), families, adults, and groups of diverse backgrounds. Min's specialty areas include anxiety, depression, parent-child/family issues. As an Asian-American therapist, she understands firsthand the effect one's cultural background can have on all aspects of life. Min strives to provide a safe and non-judgmental space for clients; and is committed to creating meaningful connections to ensure no client feels alone on their journey towards healing, growth, and empowerment.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Aetna, Anthem, Beacon, Cigna, Humana/ChoiceCare, Magellan, MHN (Health Net), Norcal Kaiser, Optum/UBH

therapists.additional_information: As a Licensed Marital and Family Therapist with over 15 years of psychotherapeutic service, I provide psychotherapy to Individuals, Couples, and Families. My Master of Arts (M.A.) in Marital and Family Therapy with a specialization in Art Therapy is from Loyola Marymount University in Los Angeles.  The program is well-respected & one of the oldest graduate programs for Art Therapists. My background in the politics of gender, race, class, sexual orientation and the corporate (Fortune 50) technology world provide many benefits in treatment. In addition to my private practice, I concurrently work in designing therapeutic landscapes.

I have worked with many different people who have various goals for therapy. For some it is to work through their anxiety and depression, and for others it may be to talk through their current struggles with relationships, identity, career, parenting or loss of a loved one. I work with clients to help them create their own understanding of how they want to live and to support them as they explore, meet and overcome their challenges. My relationship with each client is unique and an important part of therapy. I incorporate different types of treatment and work from an inclusive perspective of each client's experience.

I have over 7 years of experience working with individuals and families in inpatient and outpatient settings and have specialized training in addictions counseling, infant mental health, complex trauma processing, and systemic therapy. As an adoptee of immigrant parents, I uphold cultural humility while helping families feel more connected.
My goal as a therapist is to create a supportive space for clients to be brave with their feelings and to build on their natural strengths to develop tools and increased awareness for lasting growth. I see each individual as unique and center treatment on the client’s specific needs and situation.

I'm a cis Indian-American man of color and licensed clinical social worker.  People often describe me as empathetic, thoughtful, grounded, and with a good sense of humor.  I'm skilled in helping people move through trauma, anxiety, depression, grief, relationship, and family issues.  I specialize in working with mostly people of color ages 18+, survivors of abuse and violence, and people working toward social change.

Sandy is a Chinese-American daughter of refugees of the Vietnam War. Her father is Cantonese from Guangzhou and her mother is Teo-Chew, both growing up in Vietnam. Sandy is the only daughter of five siblings, spending much of her youth in Texas. Her first career in corporate sales at a Fortune 500 company made her realize how connecting with other human beings on healing felt more authentic than remaining in the business world. She considers it a calling and a privilege to work on healing inter-generational trauma and to cultivate the resilience, power, and joy that is possible when we make space for deep, committed healing.

Naomi is a psychotherapist and art therapist based in California offering online therapy.  She uses creative, goal-oriented, and holistic techniques that meet you in the comfort of your home.  She particularly enjoys working with mindfulness, cultural issues, and destigmatizing mental health.  Therapy with Naomi often includes growing insight to better understand yourself, developing skills to manage stress, and capitalizing on your strengths to cultivate an authentic, intentional, and meaningful life.

I specialize in the treatment of eating disorders in adolescents and young adults and utilize techniques from CBT, psychodynamic, narrative, and family systems theories. My approach is weight-inclusive, and based on the frameworks of Intuitive Eating (IE) and Health at Every Size (HAES). I am LGBTQ+ affirming and neurodivergent affirming.

I use evidence-informed therapy to treat a range of concerns including race-based stress, post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), anxiety, insomnia, depression, loneliness, and interpersonal difficulties. In meeting each of my clients, I apply the dialectical balance between acceptance and change, holding firm that “at each moment we are all doing the best we can, and we can also do better”. As a radical behaviorist, I work primarily from Dialectical Behavior Therapy, Functional Analytic Psychotherapy, and Acceptance and Commitment Therapy, in order to enable my clients to find ways to live more fully.

Charles Zeng specializes in depth psychology and affirmative psychotherapy. After working in non-profit community mental health, Charles has experience with a diverse population of adults, adolescents, couples, and has facilitated process groups with folks around issues of vulnerability and self-acceptance. With a non-judgmental approach, Charles wants to stay curious in getting to know his clients so that they can feel safe about asking for what they need. There is often so much shame around not knowing who we are, Charles is here to help tame that shame, and work together to uncover our deeper sense of self.

Jennifer Hsia, Ph.D., is a psychologist specializing in health/medical anxiety, chronic pain, and issues related to racial/ethnic identify. She completed her Ph.D. in clinical psychology at University of South Dakota in and postdoctoral fellowship at the San Diego VA. She is passionate about promoting social justice and equity. Professionally, previous positions include staff psychologist at college/university counseling centers and Assistant Professor in a clinical psychology PhD program.

Taking the first steps in being a better you is acknowledging that you need help and asking for that help. The biggest change happens when clients are ready to put in the work in being better versions of themselves. I previously worked at outpatient and forensic residential mental health settings. My focus population are adults who deal with trauma, life transitions, self-esteem and relationship issues. I have experience in Cognitive Behavioral Therapy, Motivational Interviewing, Crisis Oriented Recovery Services and Solution Focused Therapy and will pull from these modalities to tailor to your needs.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: United, Aetna, Humana, Cigna, Anthem, Optum, Oscar

therapists.additional_information: A native of southern California, Sean earned his B.A. in Psychology from Pomona College, an M.A. in Counseling Psychology and then his Ph.D. in Counseling Psychology from the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign. He has worked as a clinical counselor at various counseling centers and is currently the Director of Counseling Services at the ArtCenter College of Design in Pasadena. His clinical experience includes work with individuals, couples, and groups, serving adult clients from a diverse range of backgrounds and identities.

I began my vocation as a psychotherapist in 2013 after working in different areas in academia for more than 10 years. I absolutely love what I do! I find excitement in empowering my clients to believe that their lives can be transformed no matter where they are.

I'm an EMDR-trained therapist experienced in helping you neutralize that emotional reaction you have when entering certain situations that you know "shouldn't" bother you anymore.

Dr. Luu is a licensed clinical psychologist with an extensive background in community-based mental health and pediatric consultation. She received her Doctorate in Clinical Psychology from the California School of Professional Psychology at Alliant International University, San Francisco and completed her post-doctoral training at the Department of Psychiatry at Children's Hospital Oakland where she was the Chief Resident of Rotation. In addition to pediatric psychology, she has a keen interest in advancing social justice through her administrative, academic, and clinical work.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Blue Cross Anthem, Aetna, Magellan, Beacon Health Options, Beacon Health Strategies, Tricare, Optum, Medicare

therapists.additional_information: I am a Licensed Clinical  Social Worker (LCSW) trained in CBT, DBT, psychoanalytic, complex trauma, and internal family systems theory, as well as the Gottman Relationship Method for couples counseling. In therapy sessions I use emotionally-focused therapy to address depression, anxiety, attachment issues, cross-cultural and racial issues, for adult individuals and couples. Poet Mary Oliver asked the question, "What will you do with this one wild and precious life?" It would be my privilege to hold a safe space for you to work out your answer this question and to be a part of your growth journey.

With over 14 years in the mental health field, I have a passion working with adults who are struggling with anxiety, depression, relationship challenges, multi-cultural and identity issues. I strive to provide a nurturing environment in therapy for people, especially for those who have historically been marginalized, to thrive.

Harry Dixon, MA, LMHC, LPCC is a gay Korean American cis male licensed professional clinical counselor providing individual counseling in San Diego, CA as well as Seattle, WA.  He is unique among counselors in his ability to understand issues resulting from cultural and intergenerational conflicts as well as concerns and struggles around intersectional identities. He can help you navigate through these identities and help you discover the true you so that you may have a fuller and more exciting life experience.

Through self compassion, healing, peace, and acceptance of ourselves, you can go from where you are to where you want to be. I believe healing lies in understanding all parts of us, including the cultures, experiences, and beliefs that we carry in our present selves. I also believe that everyone can live a life reflective of what they enjoy, desire, and love. With judgment free acceptance, I use the therapeutic space for everyone to be their genuine self in this journey of being. And I consider it a great joy to collaborate with you in your own unique journey of restorative experiences.

Michelle is a Therapist, Clinical Supervisor and a Trainer that educates on topics of cultural responsive and inclusive care. She understands how sometimes the root of our distress can come from the pressure and expectations we learned from our society and our families. The distress can sometimes be debilitating where it can look like depression, anxiety, and even burn out. Her style is collaborative where she will not impose values and methods on you that doesn’t feel right. Instead, it is about eliciting what fits and works for you where you will feel at peace with how you show up in your relationships, household and career.

My clinical practice is informed by a mix of psychoanalysis, solution-focused, motivational interviewing and cognitive behavioral therapy. I provide support, guidance and reflection to the entire life spectrum (children, youth, adults, families and couples) as they face life difficulties, transitions, pain and suffering. My work with you is to utilize insights to create awareness, change, healing and restoration towards emotional wellness.

My clinical experiences include: primary care, outpatient community mental health, geriatric home visits, early intervention, early childhood consultation and school-based mental health.

Chay works with anxious perfectionists to find the balance between excellence and energetic restoration. She has lived experience of a lifelong overachiever, and it is clear to her how exhausting it is to juggle so many things and wear so many hats: you can even start to lose what it means to be yourself. If you are ready to release yourself from the endless cycle of ‘never feeling good enough’ and ‘needing to constantly be my best’, then Chay can provide you with both the empathy and safety you need to explore those emotions with the tools that will get rid of your anxiety for good and help you find the answers for what you need to do next.

Cindy Shu is a private practice clinician with an office located in San Francisco and currently offering telehealth to residents of California. Cindy Shu primarily works with Asian American working professionals who need support around managing depression, anxiety, and work-related stress. Cindy Shu offers support to first generation Asian Americans who are exploring their own cultural identities while navigating familial dynamics, expectations, and intergenerational trauma.  Cindy Shu works collaboratively, authentically, and empowers clients to advocate for themselves and use their voice to help deepen connections with themselves and others

In today’s fast paced society it is easy to feel burned out and overwhelmed without support and self-care. Our emotional well-being affects our productivity, relationships, and impact on our self. I specialize in helping individuals with stress, frustration, and anxiety related to work, relationships, school, and life transitions.

Therapy can be seen as an emotional and personal development process. I offer a free 20 minute consultation to help you get a sense of how it’s like for us to work together. Please contact me to schedule a consultation.

Dr. Chong is a clinical health psychologist interested in interdisciplinary care. She completed a postdoctoral fellowship at Stanford University School of Medicine and received her Ph.D. in clinical psychology from UT Southwestern. Dr. Chong promotes the use of a biopsychosocial approach to help individuals living with chronic health conditions improve their functioning and quality of life.

I help Filipina/x, women & couples work through anxiety, communication, family/relationship wounds, self-defeating thoughts & old patterns. I serve as a guide, ally and collaborator in your healing journey, while also helping you develop awareness and life skills.

I identify as second generation Filipina-American and fourth generation Chinese-American who was born and raised in the Bay Area. I have an interdisciplinary style with foundations in Cognitive Behavioral Therapy (CBT) and have helped people struggling with endeavors such as anxiety, depression, multicultural issues, multigenerational issues, relationship issues, difficult life transitions, and stress. If I am not the best person to help with your situation, I can help find an appropriate referral.

I am a first generation Filipina-American psychotherapist and healer. I specialize in working with clients who identify as being part of the Filipino diaspora.  My practice is psychodynamically oriented, trauma-informed, and eclectic. I help clients identify and unwind the root causes of their mental-emotional pain, so they can understand, heal, and move forward in life.

I specialize in working with 1.5 – 2nd generation immigrants and children of immigrants on issues such as anxiety, work stress, intergenerational trauma,  and cultural identity issues. I want to learn how your unique environment and experiences have shaped who you are today and the challenges that may occur as a result. I tend to be very active and engaged in sessions with my clients and enjoy discussing practical tools that may be helpful. I seek to understand you as you see yourself and provide treatment that aligns with your strengths and values.

Hi! I'm Abigail and I help women learn the tools to get rid of anxiety and depression so they can feel confident about themselves. My style is collaborative and practical. I like to think of myself as a thought partner and coach to help you become the best version of yourself. I take a holistic approach to your healing and integrates ACT, IFS, and somatic protocols.

Specialties: Multi-Racial, ethnic, and cultural identity, Women’s Leadership, and Perinatal Mental Health

When I'm not seeing clients she’s making Art, chasing the sunshine, and reading Tarot with friends.

I'm a bicultural Vietnamese & Chinese American daughter of refugees raised as an occupier of Muwekma Ohlone native land (Bay Area, CA). I hold empowering space for people to reconnect with their wholeness by slowing down, cultivating compassion, and alchemizing pain into healing and growth. I believes that collective liberation starts from within: bringing clarity and balance to our internal worlds will allow us to reclaim and actualize our dreams through meaningful action.

I am supervised by Stephanie Yuen, LMFT.

I have 20 years of experience working with diverse multicultural populations, providing clinical supervision, and training  for psychology, social work and MFT interns. At the heart of my work with children, teens, adults and families is the centrality of relationships. Susan works from the foundation that people are the experts of their own lives. My approach is collaborative, strengths-based and grounded in cultural humility. I specialize in treating anxiety, depression, trauma, life transitions, parenting issues, and grief and loss.

As an adult, do your parents still disapprove of you? Do you believe that you are not good enough?  You try to please others and feel guilty when you want to do something for yourself. 
I help Asian American adults who struggle with perfectionism, guilt, and self-criticism find freedom. I get what it is like to grow up in a family feeling not good enough and to never allow yourself to be you. I get what it is like to always put others' needs before yourself, and to have difficulty expressing what you want out of fear, guilt, and shame. 
Contact me for a free consultation to learn more about how to find freedom from anxiety, and shame.

I work with adults experiencing a wide range of difficulties, including anxiety and mood disorders, grief and loss, and trauma. I also provide therapy to couples looking to improve their relationship by addressing issues such as, communication, trust, and intimacy. I provide a safe space for my clients to express their emotions and experiences, because I believe this is fundamental in fostering the therapeutic relationship. As an immigrant, I am passionate about working with immigrants and adult children of immigrants who experience stressors, such as balancing a bicultural/multicultural identity and navigating the barriers of a new country.

My family immigrated to the U.S. from Vietnam when I was eight years old. My decision to go into the mental health field stems from my own immigration experiences and bicultural identity. I am interested in helping others navigate the transitions and challenges in their lives. 

One of my areas of interests is in the area of Asian American psychology, particularly in the areas of acculturation stress and bicultural identity. I enjoy in working with adult children from immigrant families as there are sometimes cultural and generational differences between parents and children that could negatively impact one's mental health.

I believe at our core that we are all capable of living as our most authentic selves. I aim to create a nurturing and safe environment to work alongside you and remind you of who that authentic person is. My approach is warm, accepting, and non-judgmental, where you can bring all of who you are to feel seen, heard, and valued. As a second generation Asian American woman, I understand the stigma that mental health can hold. I know from firsthand experience, however, the effectiveness that therapy can have as a healing tool when we embrace our vulnerability. In our work together, emotions will be normalized and our healing journey can begin.

Janice is an Associate Marriage and Family Therapist who obtained her Master’s Degree from San Francisco State University. She had worked with a diverse population of children and their families experiencing a wide variety of mental health concerns including depression, anxiety, and trauma in both community mental health and school-based settings. Janice believes that every individual has the potential to grow and build meaningful relationships with others and with the self by providing clients with compassion, empathy, and unconditional positive regard.

Having immigrated to the United States during my early adolescence, I experienced firsthand the impact of cultural diversity and implications of self-concept and interpersonal relationships. Therefore, I strive to provide my clients with culturally sensitive care and a grace-filled shame-free safe space for clients to process, explore, heal, grow, and celebrate. I offer evidence-based psychotherapy to help clients navigate challenges in interpersonal relationships, emotion regulations, life transitions, acculturation issues, intergenerational conflicts, faith integration, etc.  I also offer bilingual workshops to raise MH care awareness.

I have a private practice in Santa Rosa, California, and previously worked at several agencies serving the community, including survivors and family members of survivors of sexual assault and violence.  In addition, I see Veterans struggling with PTSD and Military Sexual Trauma.  I have experience in working with children, teens, and adults, and am drawn to addressing trauma and multicultural issues.  I am also bilingual and can speak Vietnamese fluently.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Beacon Health Partnership, TriWest, California Victim Compensation Board

therapists.additional_information: Brandon A. Shindo is a fourth generation Japanese American. He was born and raised in the City of Los Angeles, CA. Brandon is the Licensed Clinical Social Worker in the State of California, and the CEO and Co-Founder of K&B Therapy Inc. He specializes and is passionate in working with and advocating for young professionals, college students, and people of color (particularly those who identify as Asian American). The foundation of his professional perspective is to view things from a systematic, social constructionist, and anti-oppressive perspective. He embraces a collaborative and practical approach to harvest change/growth in his clients.

Does it ever feel like you and your partner keep having the same arguments over and over? Whether you are talking about something seemingly small or discussing important decisions for your lives, you often end up with the same fights, or at least with feeling the same way. You wonder if therapy can help, and I want you to know, that yes it can! Couple therapy has been proven to improve relationships. I specialize in providing effective couple therapy treatments and have dedicated my career towards  helping couples like you. You can work towards a better and happier relationship. Contact me for a free consultation!

I’m a licensed Marriage & Family Therapist (LMFT) and Registered Art Therapist (ATR), specializing in anxiety, depression, trauma, attachment trauma, perfectionism, high achievers, and grief. I am EMDRIA certified as an EMDR therapist and a certified Somatic Experiencing Practitioner (SEP). You are a unique individual and i attune to your needs, incorporating these therapies into our work together to heal the root of your emotional pain and guide you in your wellness journey. I believe that our experiences shape our beliefs and how we experience the world around us, including the relationship we have with ourself. We heal through connection.

Niparpon born and raised in Bangkok, Thailand as a Buddhist who attended a Catholic convent where she has learned to love all Gods and respect all beings. Niparpon is providing services for clients in Los Angeles area. Her modality is EMDR, art therapy, and trauma-inform treatment.

I am committed to delivering evidence-based treatments that are developmentally appropriate and approachable, and I tailor my interventions to fit the individual needs of each client. My therapeutic approach is empathic, intuitive, and authentic. I am passionate about empowering youth and families to find freedom from emotional suffering through both acceptance and change. I incorporate modalities such as cognitive behavioral therapy, dialectical behavior therapy, acceptance and commitment therapy, and motivational interviewing.
Postdoctoral Fellowship - Stanford U

Hi, I am Dr. Hyun, a clinical psychologist licensed in Colorado. I am originally from S. Korea and bilingual in English and Korean. I primarily work with adults but also with adolescents. I provide culturally-sensitive and trauma-informed therapy and support to those who desire to heal from past trauma, cope with emotional and/or relational struggles, or explore and learn more about themselves. I will meet with you where you are at and create a safe space where you can freely explore yourself without having the fear of being judged. Let's be on a journey together to foster a positive and fulfilling experience in your life!

Hi! I’m Alison. I want to help you have a better relationship with yourself, improve your life, and help you navigate challenges you face. 
I have a specialty for working with adult, Asian adoptees, but believe that no one should have to work through difficult times in their life alone. Feeling isolated in your experiences, relationships, depression, can be really painful. Therapy can be a key to unlocking ways for you to heal. 
I offer a free 15 minute phone consultation to see if I am a good fit for you.

I am a Licensed Clinical Psychologist working with adolescents, adults, and couples who are experiencing a wide variety of concerns. I specialize in treating trauma, grief, anxiety, and depression. I also have experience working with life transitions, identity development, relationship concerns, family of origin issues, college students, and adoptees and former foster youth. In addition to practicing in Colorado, I am authorized by PSYPACT to provide teletherapy to clients in several other states. My approach to therapy is rooted in attachment, person-centered, multicultural, and trauma-informed frameworks.

I am a Licensed Clinical Social Worker (LCSW), and I specialize in working with adult individuals who are struggling with depression, anxiety, self-esteem issues, attachment trauma, and/or challenges within adoption. I utilize a mind-body therapeutic approach that draws largely from the Internal Family Systems (IFS) model. I am drawn towards understanding how our environment, family, culture, and life experience have influenced the ways in which we relate to ourselves and others. I believe that we can naturally have multiple feelings at once, all valid, and each holding valuable information.

Through a culturally responsive approach and trauma informed and social justice lens, I help clients build a sense of hope through acceptance, compassion, and empowerment.

Asian American psychologist, providing individual and couples therapy in DC and VA. I'm a certified Emotionally Focused Couples Therapist, and love seeing couples grow in their emotional intimacy and communication. I specialize in working with anxiety, depression, relationship difficulties, and identity and cultural issues.

I am a Licensed Mental Health Counselor in the state of Florida with over 15 years of combined life coaching, executive coaching, and psychotherapy/ counseling experience. I have had the honor of working with clients across a broad spectrum of lived experiences. I have worked with clients experiencing anxiety, depression, LGBTQIA+ identifying clients, relationship issues, career challenges, self-esteem, grief, substance abuse, trauma, racial inequity, & much more. 

My counseling style is a blend of Psychodynamic and Cognitive Behavioral Therapy as well as other modes, tailoring to my clients' needs. I look forward to working with you.

I offer an approach that is strengths-based, compassionate, and goal-oriented. I have extensive experience working with people of diverse cultural backgrounds and am sensitive to cross-cultural transitions, processes of acculturation, and diversity issues. In addition to providing life transition counseling, I specialize in treating anxiety, depression and relationship issues.

I focus on empowering my clients to recognize how societal, cultural, political, and overall expectations impact their well-being and notice the need for change- not just adjustments. I work from an intersectional (multi-focused, no one right way) lens with my clients to de-stigmatize shame, guilt, and fear to cultivate and create lasting growth.

Jennifer Hsia, Ph.D., is a psychologist specializing in health/medical anxiety, chronic pain, and issues related to racial/ethnic identify. She completed her Ph.D. in clinical psychology at University of South Dakota in and postdoctoral fellowship at the San Diego VA. She is passionate about promoting social justice and equity. Professionally, previous positions include staff psychologist at college/university counseling centers and Assistant Professor in a clinical psychology PhD program.

Mental Health, especially in the minority cultures, is a touchy subject. It’s difficult to talk about and even more difficult to do something about. The most important thing in therapy is finding the right therapist for you.

As a first generation, South Asian-American women, I understand both cultures and the struggles that come with trying to blend the two. I strive to create an environment in which clients feel comfortable and at ease to facilitate sharing. You are the expert on your life and your experiences. I am here to help you gain better understanding of yourself so you can feel more confident in your decisions and in life.

Human connection is an essential part of life. From the time we’re born, we require such connection to survive and flourish. In the age of technology, we’re engaging more with social media and less with actual people, and we can find ourselves feeling increasingly alone and disconnected. Additionally, Western ideals champion the individual as opposed to the collective, leading to more feelings of isolation. But it doesn't have to be this way. By utilizing psychodynamic frameworks that highlight the importance of insight and understanding, I will help you uncover the sources of your suffering so that you may live the life you want.

I am a Board-Certified Clinical Psychologist currently serving: GA, FL, DC, IL, TX, AL, VA, AZ, CO, DE, MO, NE, NV, NH, NC, OK, PA, UT, KY & WV. As a South Asian woman, I understand the complex cultural and societal norms and values of our community that can significantly impact our mental health. My practice is both evidence-based and culturally-informed, allowing me to tailor treatment for each individual. I utilize Cognitive-Behavioral Therapy (CBT) techniques in my practice while always maintaining an empathic, person-centered approach. I also conduct ADHD, diagnostic & psychological evaluations/testing.

Both my life and professional experiences have shaped my work as a therapist. My life experience includes growing up as a child of Taiwanese immigrants, living overseas in Europe as an adult, advocating for social justice, and parenting my teens. My professional experience includes providing individual, family, and group counseling at Duke University Medical Center, Elon University Counseling Center, and multiple behavioral health agencies. I completed my Bachelors in Psychology and my Masters in Social Work with a Mental Health concentration at the University of North Carolina at Chapel Hill.

I am a 1.5 generation Chinese American board certified psychologist who specializes in cultural identity, relationships, Asian American mental health, and emotionally focused therapy. I conduct individual and couples therapy. I also conduct psychological testing for a range of issues, including ADHD, learning disabilities, overall mental health, and personality exploration. My passion is working with people of color to increase insight and connection, process and heal past wounds, and identify values for future goals.

therapists.additional_information:
As a inclusive and liberation-oriented therapist striving to decolonize mental health treatment and healing, I incorporate an ethical framework of psychotherapy, spiritual and ancestral healing to encourage optimal changes in the mind, community, body, and spirit. I can support you in overcoming stuckness, ambivalence, breaking unhelpful life patterns, and finding your voice and confidence.

My lived experience as a First Generation American, mother, military veteran, and military spouse, alongside my formal education, training, and clinical knowledge allows me to support and guide in a meaningful way where you feel validated and heard.

I consider it an honor to work with clients and to be a part of their therapeutic journeys. To bear witness to the wide range of struggle and strength in people and to get to offer support for them is both humbling and rewarding. My goal is to create a judgement-free, open, and safe environment for you to be your authentic self, to strive toward the kind of life you want to live and the version of yourself you want to be, and to explore anything else you might bring into therapy.

As a first-generation Asian immigrant myself, I dedicate my practice to Asian, bi/multicultural individuals, immigrants, LGBTQIA+, and other marginalized communities. I am passionate about working with individuals from different cultural backgrounds, exploring how complex identities and unique personal experiences have shaped us into who we are. I specialize in addressing anxiety, complex trauma, relationship issues, stress, cultural identity, family conflict, grief, self-esteem, and other issues. I strive to support people to heal from and reconcile with cultural/inter-generational conflicts and traumatic experiences.

therapists.additional_information: As a therapist, I am committed to creating an affirming space within which to guide you through life’s stressors and challenges in order to improve your quality of life. My therapeutic approach is integrative and relational, borrowing from a wide range of orientations depending on what is most helpful to your work together. Clients can expect to achieve relief from stress and anxiety, increased personal growth, and an improved understanding of themselves and their relationships.
therapists.what_insurance_accepted: Blue Cross & Blue Shield (BCSB) PPO, Cigna PPO

therapists.additional_information: I am grateful for every client that allows me to enter into their story and journey with them in the process of self-exploration, growth, and healing. I see this as a privilege and I am honored to be able to walk alongside my clients in these ways.

I use a varied/adaptive approach to therapy, with a focus on mindfulness, building self-awareness, and exploring how your thoughts affect your mood and emotions (a.k.a. CBT and DBT). I also use EMDR when client's feel stuck or need a different approach to treatment. I meet you where you are at with how you see your struggles. Also, as a social worker I keep a social justice view and consider how oppressive systems may impact your mental health.

In my practice, I am committed to offering space for you to learn more about yourself and how you show up in the many roles in your life so you can be more yourself in all parts of your life.

Amanda is a Licensed Professional Counselor (LPC) with a BSc (Hons) in Psychological Studies in Singapore and an MA in Mental Health Counseling at Trinity Evangelical Divinity School (TEDS) in Deerfield, Illinois. She is also a certified Illinois Domestic Violence Professional (ICVP). A typical counseling session may look like processing past hurts and messages you have learned and transforming them in such a way that brings healing and long-lasting change in the present. Her priority is the counseling relationship and your well-being.

Justina is a Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist who has worked with individuals, couples, and families as young as five years old all the way to older adulthood. She has experience working through a variety of issues including anxiety, depression, bereavement, life transitions, self-confidence, multicultural issues, religious issues, domestic violence, and marriage/relationship issues.

Justina’s warm approach helps clients feel at ease and tap into their strengths so they can work towards emotional and relational healing.

I take a strength-based and resilience-focused approach to assist children, adolescents, and adults find healing, success and happiness. I will be a guide on your journey to recovery from trauma, a facilitator as you learn coping skills and a partner as you navigate transitions. 
I am here to help you or your child towards healing and personal development. I utilize many different modalities to connect with my clients and develop life skills. I also have experience providing counseling across many communities including immigrants/immigrant families and with Black, Indigenous and People of Color (BIPOC).

I have been a Licensed Clinical Professional Counselor in Maine since 1998. I am also a Focusing Oriented Therapist (www.focusing.org), which allows me to work with clients from around the world. I speak mandarin and English. I am a practicing Buddhist and teach meditation. Please refer to my website: www.jingye-counseling.com

My approach to counseling is evidence-based and integrative. I combine cognitive-behavioral therapy (CBT) and feminist therapy in order to support my clients in their journeys. I try my best to ensure that every technique I use is person-centered and multicultural - my goal is to use my clients’ worldviews and values to shape and guide each intervention appropriately.

I am a licensed clinical psychologist in Virginia working primarily with clients in VA, D.C., and MD. Through PSYPACT, I can provide teletherapy to clients in 17+ states. Before opening my own practice, I worked with individuals and couples at a group practice, and before that at Swarthmore College’s Counseling and Psychological Services. I also have experience working with clients in outpatient and inpatient hospitals, community mental health clinics, and a private school. Through a culturally responsive approach and trauma informed and social justice lens, I help clients build a sense of hope through acceptance, compassion, and empowerment.

I am a Licensed Clinical Art Therapist and Counselor in Maryland. I have experience providing individual, family, and group therapy services to children, adolescents, and adults. In addition to private practice, I have worked in a variety of settings and have significant experience as a school-based therapist and community-based therapist.

SuMing is a clinical social worker licensed in MA. She currently has a private practice in Arlington, MA where she provides individual, couple and family therapy. She specializes in working with people who face systemic and internalized oppression. As a biracial woman of Asian descent, she has a particular fondness for working with other AAPI identifying people.

SuMing believes in the inherent worth of all people and is dedicated to helping her clients find their liberation through a deeper knowing of self and connection through relationship. She is committed to dismantling the ways that systemic oppression impacts mental health.

As a inclusive and liberation-oriented therapist striving to decolonize mental health treatment and healing, I incorporate an ethical framework of psychotherapy, spiritual and ancestral healing to encourage optimal changes in the mind, community, body, and spirit. I can support you in overcoming stuckness, ambivalence, breaking unhelpful life patterns, and finding your voice and confidence.

I am a licensed clinical psychologist who specializes in the assessment and treatment of anxiety, panic, phobias, OCD, and related disorders in college students and young adults. I also work with clients looking to effectively navigate and cope with current life stressors (e.g., work challenges, interpersonal relationships, transitions). I use evidenced-based techniques in my work with clients, and primarily from a cognitive behavioral therapy (CBT) perspective. I use a collaborative and warm approach, working with clients to better understand their anxieties or challenges and encouraging them to become their own therapists over time.

Dr. Yenkuei Chuang is a mindfulness-based licensed psychologist and an ordained member of Zen Master Thich Nhat Hanh’s Order of Interbeing. She received her M.Ed. in Human Development from Harvard University and Ph.D. in Counseling Psychology from Stanford University. Dr. Chuang is keenly interested in helping people transform their suffering across life transitions; and cultural, gender, racial, class, and other perceived differences. Fluent in Taiwanese and English, some Mandarin & a bit of French.

I provide a safe, compassionate environment that is supportive and free from judgment. My style incorporates cognitive-behavioral (skill building) and psychodynamic (insight-oriented) approaches in an effort to improve your overall functioning, find a deeper understanding of yourself, and foster personal growth. I specialize in treating college students and young adults and am drawn towards understanding how our environment, family, culture, and life experience have influenced how we relate to ourselves and others.

I am a licensed clinical psychologist, DEI consultant, supervisor, educator, and writer.
​
I currently facilitate BIPOC groups at the Danielsen Institute-Boston University, and Cambridge Health Alliance-Harvard Medical School training programs; serve on the Reflective Spaces/Material Places - Boston chapter steering committee; contribute as a visiting researcher at Boston University; and an ad-hoc peer reviewer for the Asian American Journal of Psychology. I previously served as the Assistant Training Director at the Danielsen Institute-Boston University, supervising and training doctoral level graduate students.

I am a Fully Licensed Psychologist in Michigan. Trained as a generalist, I have extensive experience working with anxiety, depression, eating disorders, and trauma. My clinical interests include identity development, empowerment of individuals with marginalized identity, and the impact of systemic oppression on individual's mental health. I work with clients from diverse backgrounds regarding age, gender, nationality, race, religion, sexual orientation, and  SES. I have also worked in a variety of settings, including a domestic violence shelter, children’s hospital, community mental health clinic, and university counseling centers.

I believe that people are always doing the best they can, given the resources they currently have. I specialize in helping you achieve liberation from oppressive systems through creating your own narrative of freedom and wellness. I want to help you understand how the trauma of living under oppression affects your health and well-being. Together, we will work to deconstruct the views, beliefs, and values that are holding power over you and getting in the way of finding your own inner peace.

Sally is a licensed clinical social worker with experience working with adults of all ages.  She is Korean by birth and was raised by white parents after being adopted at age 5.  As a transracial who has explored her own story, she finds meaning in helping other adoptees, trans-racial adoptees, parents, family, friends, adoption workers, and pastors understand the impacts of relinquishment and adoption on adoptees and them.  She also specializes in loss and grief, relationship issues, codependency, adjustment disorders, depression, anxiety, Perinatal Mood and Anxiety Disorders, and helping people deal with daily stressors.

Hi, I'm Amy! I'm a licensed psychologist specializing in child and young adult mental health. I work with bright, sensitive children with big emotions and behavior and their parents. I also specialize in working with college students, graduate students, and early career professionals experiencing perfectionism, stress, and burn out.

Cameron Lee Small has been working to raise consciousness about faith, child welfare, and mental health since 2012, after meeting his biological mother in Korea. Trans-racially adopted and founder of Therapy Redeemed, he holds a Master’s in Counseling Psychology from University of Wisconsin-Madison and is a licensed professional clinical counselor. Cam is PACC certified, and registered as an accredited service provider through TAC via Center for Adoption Support and Education. He is also a vetted clinician with MN ADOPT. He provides services online from Minneapolis, Minnesota, where he lives with his wife and family. Insta: @therapyredeemed

Sarah offers therapy for people looking for compassion, accountability, and even humor in their therapy experience. While encouraging clients to explore their own familial and cultural experiences, Sarah welcomes conversations about race, gender, class, power, and sexuality. Sarah supports exploration of how components like history, social justice, and popular culture shape our lives and inform our mental health. Identity, racial trauma, life transitions, those impacted by the legal system, adoption, & unconventional relationships are some of Sarah's areas of interest. She is also a trained Brainspotting therapist.

My work is informed through a multicultural integrative lens and I work with my clients to explore conflict and tension, navigate internal experiences, and change their narrative to operate more effectively. Therapy is a unique experience for each individual and I adjust my approach and style to account for your unique needs and challenges, while providing a safe, warm, and affirming space.

Crystal approaches her therapy clients with empathy and unconditional positive regard. By creating a safe space for open communication, she aims to assist individuals, their significant others, and extended family members through various life stages. Crystal challenges clients to "search deeper" within themselves to improve their interpersonal relationships, promoting relief beyond symptom reduction.

Christine Lee is a 2nd-generation Korean-American raised in New York City. She is extremely proud and humbled to be the first in her family to graduate post-secondary education at Barnard College at Columbia University, and earn her PhD in Clinical Psychology from the Ferkauf Graduate School of Psychology at Yeshiva University. She is a neuropsychologist at the Center for Neuropsychological Services at Northwell Health. She provides neuropsychological and psychodiagnostic assessment across the lifespan practice (ages 5 and up). She is not accepting new therapy clients at this time.

Race, class, and gender are at the forefront in my work with survivors of complex trauma. I help queer and trans immigrant communities with mental health challenges related to their lived experiences of abuse and neglect, long-term grief, and intergenerational trauma.

Sessions are a safe, nonjudgmental place for you to explore issues of sex and intimacy as well as emotional wounds experienced with partners and families. My clinical modalities are psychodynamic and experiential. A few of the ways we’ll work together to make sense of traumatic experiences are through body-based strategies, trauma narratives, and emotionally focused therapy.

Welcome, it's nice to meet you! Whether this is your first time in therapy or not, everyone deserves a space to feel heard, seen, and understood. Although I adopt a client-centered approach with psychodynamic perspectives; I aim to tailor the therapeutic process to every client's needs and/or wants. It is my belief that although therapists are the experts of the process, the client is the expert of his or her own experience.

As a woman of color therapist, I am passionate about working with women and the Asian American population, surrounding themes of identity and empowerment.

Peggy is a Licensed Marriage and Family Therapist with a private practice located in New York City. She treats clients from a humanistic and transpersonal perspective. She is also a certified Life Coach and obtained her certification from the Institute of Professional Excellence in Coaching (iPEC). Peggy is Chinese American and fluent in Mandarin.

Hi there! My name is Catherine and I’m a counseling intern in the beautiful state of Oregon. It’s a privilege to be able to walk alongside folks, and I find it particularly rewarding to provide space for those with marginalized identities. My counseling style is warm but directive, and my aim is to provide a safe space for you to be able to process through your thoughts and emotions. My specialties include trauma and anxiety and I enjoy working on racial identity work as well.

I primarily serve first and second-generation immigrants, people of color, survivors of childhood abuse and domestic violence, individuals navigating imposter syndrome and identity development. My counseling is person-centered and systems-based (i.e. I take someone's different backgrounds into account while also recognizing that each person is unique), and I work to incorporate cultural humility into counseling by acknowledging that social justice work is always evolving, and I need to do my part to keep learning as a practitioner. 

As a Registered LPC-Intern in Oregon, I am supervised by Summer Brown, LMFT.
